  1044	---
  1045	
  1046	## 8. Trust & Security Model
  1047	
  1048	### 8.1 Threat Boundaries
  1049	
  1050	| Boundary | Risk | Mitigation |
  1051	|---|---|---|
  1052	| `cli_plugins:` YAML from untrusted repo | Low — runs only the declared binary | Binary validated at load time (`--version` check). Subprocess isolation via `subprocess.run`. |
  1053	| `python_plugins:` from untrusted repo | **High** — arbitrary Python in orchestrator process | Blocked by default. Requires `--allow-python-plugins`. |
  1054	| User-global plugins (`~/.unison/plugins/`) | Low — user controls these files | Only loaded when explicitly referenced in `python_plugins:`. Not auto-scanned. |
  1055	| Project-local plugins (`.unison/plugins/`) | Moderate — repo author controls these | Project-local Python plugins still require `--allow-python-plugins`. Declarative plugins use only the binary, not Python import. |
  1056	
  1057	### 8.2 The `--allow-python-plugins` Gate
  1058	
  1059	```python
  1060	# cli.py — the gate
  1061	parser.add_argument(
  1062	    "--allow-python-plugins",
  1063	    action="store_true",
  1064	    default=False,
  1065	    help="Enable Python plugin loading (Tier 2). "
  1066	         "Without this flag, only declarative 'cli_plugins:' are loaded. "
  1067	         "Python plugins execute IN-PROCESS — only use with trusted plugins."
  1068	)
  1069	```
  1070	
  1071	Without this flag:
  1072	- `cli_plugins:` entries are loaded normally (safe — they only declare binaries)
  1073	- `python_plugins:` entries cause `PluginLoadError` with a clear message
  1074	- No Python code from any plugin directory is imported
  1075	
  1076	With this flag:
  1077	- Both `cli_plugins:` and `python_plugins:` are loaded
  1078	- Python files in `~/.unison/plugins/` and `.unison/plugins/` are imported
  1079	- The user accepts the trust implication
  1080	
  1081	### 8.3 Plugin Sandboxing (Future)
  1082	
  1083	The current design runs plugins in-process. A future iteration (v2.2) will
  1084	add a subprocess-based sandbox for Python plugins:
  1085	- Load plugin in a `multiprocessing.Process` with restricted `sys.path`
  1086	- Communicate via pickle over a pipe (same `AgentRunner` protocol)
  1087	- Optional seccomp/AppArmor profile for the worker process
  1088	
  1089	This is deferred because it adds complexity and the declarative `cli_plugins:`
  1090	path already covers the common case safely.
  1091	
  1092	---
  1093	
  1094	## 9. Migration Path
  1095	
  1096	### For Existing Pipelines
  1097	
  1098	**No changes needed.** Existing `pipeline.yaml` files without `cli_plugins:` or
  1099	`python_plugins:` keys load identically. The `version` field stays at whatever
  1100	the pipeline already declares. Schema migration handles version bumps.
  1101	
  1102	### For Adding a Custom Runtime
  1103	
  1104	**Step 1:** Add a `cli_plugins:` section to `pipeline.yaml`:
  1105	
  1106	```yaml
  1107	cli_plugins:
  1108	  gemini:
  1109	    binary: gemini-internal
  1110	    args: ["-p", "--output-format", "text", "-y"]
  1111	    env:
  1112	      GEMINI_API_KEY: "${GEMINI_API_KEY}"
  1113	    timeout_grace: 10
  1114	```
  1115	
  1116	**Step 2:** Change the agent's `runtime:` to the plugin name:
  1117	
  1118	```yaml
  1119	# BEFORE
  1120	agents:
  1121	  coder:
  1122	    runtime: claude
  1123	
  1124	# AFTER
  1125	agents:
  1126	  coder:
  1127	    runtime: gemini
  1128	```
  1129	
  1130	**Step 3:** Validate:
  1131	
  1132	```
  1133	$ unison validate pipeline.yaml
  1134	✓ gemini → binary: /usr/local/bin/gemini-internal
  1135	Ready to run.
  1136	```
  1137	
  1138	**Step 4:** Run as normal:
  1139	
  1140	```
  1141	$ unison run pipeline.yaml
  1142	```
  1143	
  1144	### For Python Plugin Authors
  1145	
  1146	**Step 1:** Write a plugin class (see §3.2-3.3) and drop it in
  1147	`~/.unison/plugins/`.
  1148	
  1149	**Step 2:** Declare in `python_plugins:`:
  1150	
  1151	```yaml
  1152	python_plugins:
  1153	  my-runner:
  1154	    module: my_runner
  1155	    class: MyRunnerPlugin
  1156	```
  1157	
  1158	**Step 3:** Pass the trust gate:
  1159	
  1160	```
  1161	$ unison run pipeline.yaml --allow-python-plugins
  1162	```
  1163	
  1164	---
  1165	
  1166	## 10. Open Questions
  1167	
  1168	1. **pip-installable plugins?** The current design uses file-based discovery.
  1169	   A future iteration could support entry points (`unison.plugins` group in
  1170	   `pyproject.toml`). Deferred to v2.2.
  1171	
  1172	2. **Plugin precedence between cli_plugins and python_plugins?** Currently,
  1173	   `cli_plugins` are loaded first, so a `python_plugins` entry with the same
  1174	   name as a `cli_plugins` entry is rejected as a duplicate. This is the
  1175	   safest default — it prevents ambiguous resolution.
  1176	
  1177	3. **Hot reload?** Plugins are loaded once during `PipelineLoader.load()`.
  1178	   Edits take effect on the next `unison run`. Matches existing runner behavior.
  1179	
  1180	4. **Plugin metadata?** Should plugins declare `min_unison_version`,
  1181	   `author`, `description`? Useful for debugging and the `unison validate`
  1182	   output. Deferred to v2.2.
  1183	
  1184	5. **Non-subprocess plugins (HTTP, gRPC)?** Supported via Python plugin
  1185	   `run()` override. The `AgentRunner` protocol doesn't care how
  1186	   `AgentResult` is produced. Only available via Tier 2 (Python API).
  1187	
